<h3 class="wp-block-heading" id="Dumbbell-Reverse-Lunge">Dumbbell Reverse Lunge</h3>



<p>The <a href="https://www.endomondo.com/exercise/dumbbell-reverse-lunge" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">dumbbell reverse lunge</a> is a lower-body exercise that targets the <a href="https://europepmc.org/article/nbk/nbk538193" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">glutes</a>, <a href="https://www.frontiersin.org/journals/physiology/articles/10.3389/fphys.2021.694604/full" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">hamstrings</a>, and <a href="https://europepmc.org/article/nbk/nbk513334" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">quadriceps</a>. It also engages the core for stability, making it an excellent compound movement for strength and balance. </p>



<p>The reverse lunge puts <a href="https://www.semanticscholar.org/paper/Comparative-Analysis-of-Lunge-Techniques%3A-Forward%2C-Park-Chung/d6c485f11e3365e6a577deaea27e489fca837863" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">less strain on the knees</a> compared to the forward lunge. This is because your weight is more supported by the hips instead of the pressure landing on the knee. Thus making this a joint-friendly option for building muscle and improving lower-body function.</p>



<figure class="wp-block-embed is-type-video is-provider-vimeo wp-block-embed-vimeo wp-embed-aspect-16-9 wp-has-aspect-ratio vimeo-custom"><div class="wp-block-embed__wrapper">
<iframe title="Dumbbell Reverse Lunge" src="https://player.vimeo.com/video/1000660875?dnt=1&amp;app_id=122963" width="500" height="281" frameborder="0" allow="autoplay; fullscreen; picture-in-picture; clipboard-write"></iframe>
</div><figcaption class="wp-element-caption">Dumbbell Reverse Lunge Guide. Video: Aliaksandr Makatserchyk</figcaption></figure>



<h4 class="wp-block-heading">How To Do</h4>



<ol>
<li>Start with your feet hip-width apart.</li>



<li>With palms facing inwards, hold a dumbbell in each hand.</li>



<li>Step one foot back and lower your knee toward the ground.</li>



<li>Keep your front knee directly above your ankle.</li>



<li>Push through your front heel to return to standing.</li>



<li>Repeat on the opposite leg.</li>
</ol>



<h4 class="wp-block-heading">Tips </h4>



<ul>
<li>Keep your chest lifted and shoulders back to maintain good posture.</li>



<li>Engage your core to keep your balance as you step back.</li>



<li>Avoid letting your front knee go beyond your toes.</li>



<li>Move slowly and control each rep to target muscles effectively.</li>



<li>Step far enough back to form a 90-degree angle with your front leg.</li>
</ul>



<h4 class="wp-block-heading">Optimal Sets And Reps</h4>



