<h3 class="wp-block-heading" id="Renegade-Row">Renegade Row</h3>



<p>The <a href="https://www.endomondo.com/exercise/renegade-rows" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">renegade row</a> is a challenging full-body exercise that targets the back, shoulders, core, and arms. It combines a plank position with rowing movements, improving <a href="https://www.frontiersin.org/journals/physiology/articles/10.3389/fphys.2022.852094/full" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">core stability</a> and upper-body strength. This exercise also engages the <a href="https://europepmc.org/article/NBK/nbk459392" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">obliques</a> (side abs) and stabilizer muscles, making it a highly engaging movement for building strength.</p>



<figure class="wp-block-embed is-type-video is-provider-vimeo wp-block-embed-vimeo wp-embed-aspect-16-9 wp-has-aspect-ratio vimeo-custom"><div class="wp-block-embed__wrapper">
<iframe loading="lazy" title="Renegade Rows" src="https://player.vimeo.com/video/1006102009?dnt=1&amp;app_id=122963" width="500" height="281" frameborder="0" allow="autoplay; fullscreen; picture-in-picture; clipboard-write"></iframe>
</div><figcaption class="wp-element-caption">Renegade Row Guide. Video: Aliaksandr Makatserchyk</figcaption></figure>



<h4 class="wp-block-heading">How To Do</h4>



<ol>
<li>Start in a plank position, holding a dumbbell in each hand.</li>



<li>Keep your feet shoulder-width apart and toes tucked for better stability.</li>



<li>Row one dumbbell toward your ribcage by bending your elbow and lifting the weight up.</li>



<li>Lower the dumbbell back to the original plank position. Repeat on the other side.</li>
</ol>



<h4 class="wp-block-heading">Tips</h4>



<ul>
<li>Keep your body straight and avoid twisting your hips during the row.</li>



<li>Ensure your shoulders remain back and down. They shouldn’t be tensed up near your ears.</li>



<li>Engage your core throughout the movement to prevent <a href="https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s10439-015-1248-0" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">spinal loading</a> and excessive arching.</li>



<li>Use controlled movements to prevent shifting your weight and becoming misaligned.</li>



<li>Keep your elbows close to your body instead of flaring outwards.</li>



<li>It is more important to use the correct form than it is to use heavy weights. If the movement feels too unstable, use less weight and focus on perfecting your technique first.</li>
</ul>



<h4 class="wp-block-heading">Optimal Sets And Reps</h4>



