<h3 class="wp-block-heading" id="Dumbbell-Bench-Press">Dumbbell Bench Press</h3>



<p>The <a href="https://www.endomondo.com/exercise/dumbbell-bench-press" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">dumbbell bench press</a> is a simple variation of a classic exercise. It engages the <a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30855905/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">chest</a>, shoulders, and <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK536996/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">triceps</a>. This exercise helps build upper-body strength and muscle tone. Dumbbells allow for a greater range of motion than a barbell, leading to better muscle activation.</p>



<figure class="wp-block-embed is-type-video is-provider-vimeo wp-block-embed-vimeo wp-embed-aspect-16-9 wp-has-aspect-ratio vimeo-custom"><div class="wp-block-embed__wrapper">
<iframe loading="lazy" title="Dumbbell Bench Press" src="https://player.vimeo.com/video/962955622?dnt=1&amp;app_id=122963" width="500" height="281" frameborder="0" allow="autoplay; fullscreen; picture-in-picture; clipboard-write"></iframe>
</div><figcaption class="wp-element-caption">Dumbbell Bench Press Guide. Video: Aliaksandr Makatserchyk</figcaption></figure>



<h4 class="wp-block-heading">How To Do</h4>



<ol>
<li>Lie on a flat bench with your feet planted and knees at a 90-degree angle.</li>



<li>Hold a dumbbell in each hand at chest level with your palms facing towards your feet.</li>



<li>Press the dumbbells upward until your arms are fully extended, but don’t lock your elbows.</li>



<li>Slowly lower the dumbbells back to your chest, keeping control of the movement.</li>
</ol>



<h4 class="wp-block-heading">Tips</h4>



<ul>
<li>Keep your feet flat on the floor to stay balanced.</li>



<li><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/38974522/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">Retract your shoulder blades</a> (pull them back and together) to stabilize and protect your shoulders.</li>



<li>Engage your core to keep your body stable.</li>



<li>Allow a natural arch in your lower back. Avoid sagging or overarching.</li>



<li>Use a controlled tempo for both the pressing and lowering phases.</li>



<li>Squeeze your chest at the top of the movement for <a href="https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s00421-016-3341-y" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">better muscle activation</a>.</li>
</ul>



<h4 class="wp-block-heading">Optimal Sets And Reps</h4>



